   "Dakota Feather Wins",
   "First Place at Art Festival",
   "\u003cp\u003e\n    \u003ca href=\"http://teacheratsea.noaa.gov/books/pdf/DaftariAlphabetBook.pdf\"\u003eABC Shark Coloring Book\u003c/a\u003e\n    Illustrator, Dakota Feather, Wins First Place at \u003ca href=\"http://www.tulsaindianartfestival.com/history.html\"\u003eTulsa Indian Art Festival \u003c/a\u003e\n\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\nDakota Feather, a sixth grader at Jay Middle School and student of TAS alumna 2011,\u003ca href=\"http://teacheratsea.noaa.gov/2011/goldner.html\"\u003eJenny Goldner\u003c/a\u003e, won first place for his artwork at the 2013 Tulsa Indian Art Festival in February. Dakota sold his artwork to a festival attendee. Congratulations Dakota!\n\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\n    Dakota is the illustrator for the \u003ca href=\"http://teacheratsea.noaa.gov/books/pdf/DaftariAlphabetBook.pdf\"\u003eABC Shark Coloring Book \u003c/a\u003ethat he and his\n    classmates designed as a result of Ms. Goldner’s TAS experience aboard NOAA Ship \u003cem\u003eOregon II. \u003c/em\u003eNOAA scientists, Trey Driggers and Kristin Hannan\n    worked with Ms. Goldner and her class to edit and publish the coloring book. They later visited Jay Upper Elementary School in Jay, Oklahoma in May of 2012\n    to talk with Ms. Goldner’s class and sign the coloring books.\n\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\n    NOAA Teacher at Sea is very proud of you Dakota and we hope that you continue your work as an illustrator!\n\u003c/p\u003e",
