   "TAS Alumni Volunteer at the",
   "Maker Faire in Silver Spring, MD",
   "\u003cp\u003e\nFour TAS Alumni – \u003ca href=\"http://teacheratsea.noaa.gov/2014/le.html\"\u003eJoan Le\u003c/a\u003e (2014), \u003ca href=\"http://teacheratsea.noaa.gov/2012/peretich.html\"\u003eAmanda Peretich\u003c/a\u003e (2012), \u003ca href=\"http://teacheratsea.noaa.gov/2011/bullock.html\"\u003eElizabeth Bullock\u003c/a\u003e (2011) and \u003ca href=\"http://teacheratsea.noaa.gov/2007/martz/index.html\"\u003eElizabeth Martz \u003c/a\u003e(2007) volunteered at the NOAA booth during the  \u003ca href=\"http://makerfairesilverspring.com/\"\u003eMaker Faire\u003c/a\u003e in Silver Spring, MD on September 14, 2014. The Alumni assisted Jeannine Montgomery,\n    Outreach Specialist from NOAA’s Office of Education, with hands-on activities. The public put their ideas about buoyancy to the test during the “Boat\n    Building Challenge”. They had to design, build and load their boat to see how long it would float. Maker Faire participants also learned about how mariners\n    and cultures from around the world began making rope out of natural fibers thousands of years ago and the engineering secrets that they discovered. They\n    explored the strength of rope and unlocked some of these secrets by making ropes of their own in the “Rope Making Activity”. Over 750 families stopped by\n    the NOAA booth to check out these activities!\n\u003c/p\u003e",
   "\u003cp\u003e\nFour TAS Alumni – \u003ca href=\"http://teacheratsea.noaa.gov/2014/le.html\"\u003eJoan Le\u003c/a\u003e (2014), \u003ca href=\"http://teacheratsea.noaa.gov/2012/peretich.html\"\u003eAmanda Peretich\u003c/a\u003e (2012), \u003ca href=\"http://teacheratsea.noaa.gov/2011/bullock.html\"\u003eElizabeth Bullock\u003c/a\u003e (2011) and \u003ca href=\"http://teacheratsea.noaa.gov/2007/martz/index.html\"\u003eElizabeth Martz \u003c/a\u003e(2007) volunteered at the NOAA booth during the  \u003ca href=\"http://makerfairesilverspring.com/\"\u003eMaker Faire\u003c/a\u003e in Silver Spring, MD on September 14, 2014. The Alumni assisted Jeannine Montgomery,\n    Outreach Specialist from NOAA’s Office of Education, with hands-on activities. The public put their ideas about buoyancy to the test during the “Boat\n    Building Challenge”. They had to design, build and load their boat to see how long it would float. Maker Faire participants also learned about how mariners\n    and cultures from around the world began making rope out of natural fibers thousands of years ago and the engineering secrets that they discovered. They\n    explored the strength of rope and unlocked some of these secrets by making ropes of their own in the “Rope Making Activity”. Over 750 families stopped by\n    the NOAA booth to check out these activities!\n\u003c/p\u003e",
   "https://teacheratsea.files.wordpress.com/2014/09/amanda-and-liz.jpg?w=180",
   "Amanda Peretich (L) and Elizabeth Martz (R) helping children test their boat buoyancy and rope strength at the NOAA Booth. (Not pictured: Joan Le and Elizabeth Bullock)",
   "09/24/2014",
   "MA"
